cfDNAPro Tutorials

The purpose of this document is to show the usage of cfDNAPro R package. The examples below come from urine cfDNA profiling project.

1. Install cfDNAPro

install.packages("devtools")
library(devtools)
devtools::install("/Volumes/files/research/nrlab/group/group_folders/HAICHAO/R_package_develop/cfDNAPro/")

3. Fragment size distribution of each group

#plot the fragment size distribution of each group 

#define a list
grp_list<-list("healthy"="healthy","renal"="renal","bladder"="bladder","melanoma"="melanoma")

#generating the plots and store them in a list
result<-sapply(grp_list, function(x){
  result <-callSize(path = root_path) %>% filter(group==as.character(x)) %>% plotSinglegroup()
},simplify = F)
## setting default outfmt to df.
## setting default outfmt to df.
## setting default outfmt to df.
## setting default outfmt to df.
#multiplexing the plots in one figure
#please mind that the plots were modified by adding different elements by "+"
multiplex<-ggpubr::ggarrange(result$healthy$prop_plot+theme(axis.title.x = element_blank()),
                             result$renal$prop_plot+ theme(axis.title = element_blank()),
                             result$bladder$prop_plot+ theme(axis.title = element_blank()),
                             result$melanoma$prop_plot+ theme(axis.title = element_blank()),
                             result$healthy$cdf_plot,
                             result$renal$cdf_plot + theme(axis.title.y = element_blank()),
                             result$bladder$cdf_plot+ theme(axis.title.y = element_blank()),
                             result$melanoma$cdf_plot+ theme(axis.title.y = element_blank()),
                             labels = c("Healthy (n=27)", "Renal (n=22)", "Bladder (n=57)","Melanoma (n=49)"),
                             label.x = 0.3,
                             ncol = 4,
                             nrow = 2)
multiplex

4. Median size metrics

compare_grps<-callMetrics(root_path) %>% plotMetrics(order=order)

#modify the plots
p1<-compare_grps$median_prop_plot +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_blank(),
        axis.title.y = element_text(size=12,face="bold")) +
  theme(legend.position = c(0.7, 0.5),
        legend.text = element_text( size = 11),
        legend.title = element_blank())

p2<-compare_grps$median_cdf_plot +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::number_format(accuracy = 0.001)) +
  theme(axis.title=element_text(size=12,face="bold")) +
  theme(legend.position = c(0.7, 0.5),
        legend.text = element_text( size = 11),
        legend.title = element_blank())

#Finalize the plots
median_grps<-ggpubr::ggarrange(p1,
                       p2,
                       label.x = 0.3,
                       ncol = 1,
                       nrow = 2
                       )

median_grps

#The order and horizontal lines could be customized.
mode_bin_modify<-callMode(root_path) %>% plotMode(order = c("melanoma","glioblastoma","renal","healthy"),hline = c(167,111,81))

6. Inter-peak/valley distance

#inter peak and valley distance plot

inter_peak_dist<-callPeakdist(root_path) %>%
  plotPeakdist(order = order) +
  theme(axis.title =  element_text(size=12,face="bold"),
        legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.position = c(0.91, 0.5),
        legend.text = element_text(size = 11))
## setting default limit (i.e. the insert_size focus region) to c(35,135).
## setting default outfmt to df.
## Setting default mincount to 0.
## setting the mincount to 0.
##  setting the xlim to c(7,13). 
## 
inter_valley_dist<-callValleydist(root_path) %>%
  plotValleydist(order = order) +
  theme(axis.title =  element_text(size=12,face="bold"),
        legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.position = c(0.91, 0.5),
        legend.text = element_text(size = 11))
## setting default limit (i.e. the insert_size focus region) to c(35,135).
## setting default outfmt to df.
